snippet.textDisplay:
Its a ghazal on Raag Bhairavi(Hindustani). Hindustani music, emerged as a distinct form due to Persian influences in North India. 
 
The poet had studied classical music(Hindustani) carefully and has experimented with different ragas like dhrupad, kheyal, thumri, tappa and ghazal. The genius music Maestro Dilip Kumar Roy (Son of Dwijendralal Ray) was his Mentor and very close friend. In Kolkata he took lessons on classical music from renowned Ustads like Ustad Jamiruddin Khan. 

Nazrul believed that the 'rasa' that classical music could create could not be done with modern music. 

At young age Nazrul joined the British 49 Bengal Regiment and was posted to Karachi which lasted about two and half years. During his stay in the army, Nazrul learnt Persian from the regiment's Punjabi moulvi. Practiced music with other musical-minded soldiers to the accompaniment of local and foreign instruments and at the same time pursued literary activities in both prose and poetry. In that period he acquired the taste for Persian poems and learned the beauty of ghazals. He was under great influence of Omar Khayyam, Hafez, Molana Rumi and such. Nazrul’s most notable among translations are his translations of the rubaiya of Omar Khayyam and Hafiz.
 
He referred to Persian archetypes with as much ease as he did ancient Hindu ones. 
He used Sanskrit and Arabic metres as easily as he did traditional Bangla ones. 

In 1921 one of Nazrul's famous poem 'Kamal Pasha' demonstrated Nazrul's sense of contemporary international history and the hollowness of the Indian Khilafat movement. Nazrul was most deeply influenced by the leadership of Mostafa Kamal Pasha, who had overthrown the feudal sultanate and turned Turkey into a secular and modern republic. Nazrul was particularly impressed by the way Kamal Pasha had removed fundamentalism from Turkish society as well as got women to give up their veils. He wondered why the reforms in Turkey could not be replicated in India and Bengal. 

So what does it tell us? Nazrul belongs to no community, no religion, no nation, no land, no language. Nazrul was and will always be the singing Bird of Humanity, Freedom and Love.  

"Even though I was born in this country (Bengal), in this society, I don't belong to just this locale. I belong to the world" -- Nazrul.
